text.tspan: The first step in the design process was gathering inspiration from other portfolios. This
gave me a better understanding of what colors work and what key functionalities are
necessary. I wanted to be able to not only display my work, but also have my personality
who I am as a designer.
While writing the code for my website, my mentor stressed the importance of validating
my code every time I made changes. This allowed me to make sure there were no stray
Once that was done, I input my website into a cross-browser testing tool to ensure that
it looked the same on every type of browser and device. I was able to see any issues that
were present when the breakpoint changed to make any necessary corrections.
While going through the process of writing the code for my portfolio, I also had to make
design decisions that would create a cohesive brand. At first, I decided on a very neutral
color palette of black, white and nude, as I felt this would let the work shine through. As
I started designing my portfolio like this, I quickly realized my personality wasn't
showing through and there was a disconnect between my colorful work, bright "About
Me" photo and the rest of my website. I decided to incorporate a color palette and other
UI elements that represented me as a brand, starting with my logo.
